The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted sales growth of 20\%
&nbsp;
* 80\% capacity of fixed assets
&nbsp;
* Constant dividend payout ratio and interest expense 
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in the cost, assets, and accounts payables proportional to sales
&nbsp;
*No new external debt or equity financing

Now, let us compute the increase in the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Increase in Sales}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate of Increase}\\[12pt]
&={\$980,760}\times{20\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$196,152}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The increase in the sales amounts to \$196,152.**

Now, let us compute the projected sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Sales}&=\text{Sales}+\text{Increase in Sales}\\[12pt]
&={\$980,760}+{\$196,152}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,176,912}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected sales is \$1,176,912.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$792,960}{\$980,760}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.81}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{81\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cost in proportion to the sales is 81\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{81\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$953,298.72}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$953,298.72.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Other Expenses in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Other Expenses}&=\frac{\text{Other Expenses}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$20,060}{\$980,760}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.02}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{2\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Other Expenses in proportion to the sales is 2\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Other Expenses:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Other Expenses}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{2\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$23,538.24}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Other Expenses is \$23,538.24.**

Now, let us compute the projected taxable income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Taxable Income}&=\text{Earnings before Interest and Taxes}\\[5pt]
&-\text{Interest Paid}\\[12pt]
&={\$200,075.04}-{\$14,740}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$189,932.04}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Taxable income is \$189,932.04.**

Now, let us compute the taxes:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Taxes}&=\text{Taxable Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$189,932.04}\times{21\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$39,885.73}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected taxes is \$39,885.73.**

Now, let us compute the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Taxable Income}-\text{Taxes}\\[12pt]
&={\$189,932.04}-{\$39,885.73}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$150,046.31}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$150,046.31.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cash in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cash}&=\frac{\text{Cash}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$27,920}{\$980,760}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.03}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{3\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cash in proportion to the sales is 3\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Cash:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cash}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{3\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$35,307.36 }\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Cash is \$35,307.36 .**

Now, let us compute the percentage of accounts receivable in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Accounts Receivable}&=\frac{\text{Accounts Receivable}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$42,630}{\$980,760}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.04}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{4\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of accounts receivable in proportion to the sales is 4\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Accounts Receivable:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Accounts Receivable}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{4\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$47,076.48}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Accounts Receivable is \$47,076.48.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Inventory in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Inventory}&=\frac{\text{Inventory}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$95,910}{\$980,760}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.10}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{10\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Inventory in proportion to the sales is 10\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Inventory :
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Inventory }&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{10\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$ 117,691.20 }\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Inventory is \$ 117,691.20.**

The percentage of sales of total current assets is as follows:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Current Assets}&=\text{Cash}+\text{Accounts Receivable}+\text{Inventory}\\[12pt]
&={3\%+4\%+10\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{17\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of sales of total current assets is 17\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Current Assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Current Assets}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{17\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$200,075.04}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Current Assets is \$200,075.04.**

Now, let us compute the sales in full capacity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Full Capacity Sales}&=\frac{\text{Sales}}{\text{Capacity}}\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$980,760}{80\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,225,950}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The full capacity sales amounts to \$1,225,950.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Net Plant and Equipment in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage}&=\frac{\text{ Net Plant and Equipment}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$455,980}{\$1,225,950}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.37}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{37\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Net Plant and Equipment in proportion to the sales is 37\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Net Plant and Equipment:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Plant and Equipment}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{37\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$435,547.44}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Net Plant and Equipment is \$435,547.44.**

The percentage of sales of total assets is as follows:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&=\text{Current Assets}+\text{Fixed Assets}\\[12pt]
&={17\%+37\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{54\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of sales of total assets is 54\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Total Assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&=\text{Current Assets}+\text{Fixed Assets}\\[12pt]
&={\$200,075.04+\$435,547.44}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$635,622.48}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total assets is \$635,622.48.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Accounts Payable in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Accounts Payable}&=\frac{\text{Accounts Payable}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$71,720}{\$980,760}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.07}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{7\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Accounts Payable in proportion to the sales is 7\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Accounts Payable:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Accounts Payable}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,176,912}\times{7\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$82,383.84 }\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Accounts Payable is \$82,383.84.**

Now, let us compute the total current debt of the company:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Current Debt}&=\text{Accounts Payable}+\text{Notes Payable}\\[12pt]
&={\$82,383.84}+{\$ 17,620.00 }\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$100,003.84}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The current debt is \$100,003.84.**

Now, let us compute the dividend payout ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend Payout Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Dividend}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$39,250}{\$120,870}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.32}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{32\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend payout ratio is 32\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$150,046.31}\times{32\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$48,014.82}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected dividend is \$48,014.82.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$81,620}{\$120,870}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.68}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{68\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 68\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$150,046.31}\times{68\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$102,031.49}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected addition to the retained earnings is \$102,031.49.**

